Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into 1⁄2-inch-thick wedges. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with a large
drizzle of @cooking oil{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Roast on middle rack until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, thinly slice @tomato{1} into rounds.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{4%tablespoon}, @Dijon mustard{2%teaspoon},
1 tsp water, @garlic powder{1/2%teaspoon}, and @Old Bay Seasoning{1/2%teaspoon}.
Set aside until ready to use in Step 4.

In a #large bowl{}, combine @ground beef{10%ounce}, @Old Bay Seasoning{1/2%teaspoon},
and @Worcestershire sauce{1/4%teaspoon}. Form beef mixture into two patties (four patties
for 4 servings), each slightly wider than a burger bun. Season lightly with @pepper{}.

> Save any remaining Old Bay Seasoning and Worcestershire sauce for another use!

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add patties and cook
until browned and cooked to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

In the last ~{1-2%minutes} of cooking, top each patty with @sliced mild cheddar cheese{2%slices};
cover pan until cheese melts.

While burgers cook, wrap @corn on the cob{1} in damp #paper towels{}. Microwave until
kernels are tender and corn is cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes}. Allow to rest for ~{1%minute},
then evenly halve corn crosswise.

Halve and toast @brioche buns{2} until golden.

Spread a thin layer of Old Bay aioli on cut sides of bottom buns. Top with patties,
tomato slices, and top buns.

Divide burgers, corn, and potato wedges between plates. Serve with remaining aioli on
the side for dipping.

> Ground Meat is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.